## Key Distinction

Most systems:

👉 govern behavior after state exists  

The Millings Method™:

👉 governs what is allowed to become state—and ensures it remains valid over time  

---

## Shared Admissibility Infrastructure (SAI)

SAI is the cross-system layer that maintains a common, enforceable reference for what is admissible as signal across multiple systems.

It ensures:

- systems operate on a shared admissible signal  
- state remains aligned across systems  
- execution remains grounded in a common reality  

---

👉 Without SAI, systems remain internally coherent but diverge from each other over time.

---

## Signal Admissibility Layer (SAL)

SAL governs what is allowed to enter a system as signal.

It includes:

- identity resolution  
- domain separation  
- provenance validation  
- collision detection (HFI protocol)  
- quarantine of unverifiable inputs  

---

👉 SAL prevents mis-specified signal from becoming state.

---

## System Integrity Chain

Admissibility is not a checkpoint.

It is a continuous constraint across:

- signal  
- state  
- execution  
- reality  

---

👉 If any layer breaks, the system drifts.

---

